#Text=CHAPTER IX .
#Text=Queen
#Text=Alice
#Text=‘ Well , this IS grand !

#Text=’ said Alice . ‘ I never expected I should be a Queen so soon -- and I ’ll tell you what it is , your majesty , ’ she went on in a severe tone ( she was always rather fond of scolding herself ) , ‘ it ’ll never do for you to be lolling about on the grass like that !
#Text=Queens have to be dignified , you know ! ’

#Text=So she got up and walked about -- rather stiffly just at first , as she was afraid that the crown might come off : but she comforted herself with the thought that there was nobody to see her , ‘ and if I really am a Queen , ’ she said as she sat down again , ‘ I shall be able to manage it quite well in time . ’

#Text=Everything was happening so oddly that she did n’t feel a bit surprised at finding the Red Queen and the White Queen sitting close to her , one on each side : she would have liked very much to ask them how they came there , but she feared it would not be quite civil .
#Text=However , there would be no harm , she thought , in asking if the game was over . ‘ Please , would you tell me -- ’ she began , looking timidly at the Red Queen .
#Text=‘ Speak when you ’re spoken to ! ’
#Text=The Queen sharply interrupted her .

#Text=‘ But if everybody obeyed that rule , ’ said Alice , who was always ready for a little argument , ‘ and if you only spoke when you were spoken to , and the other person always waited for YOU to begin , you see nobody would ever say anything , so that -- ’
#Text=‘ Ridiculous ! ’ cried the Queen .

#Text=‘ Why , do n’t you see , child -- ’ here she broke off with a frown , and , after thinking for a minute , suddenly changed the subject of the conversation . ‘ What do you mean by “ If you really are a Queen ” ?
#Text=What right have you to call yourself so ? You ca n’t be a Queen , you know , till you ’ve passed the proper examination .
#Text=And the sooner we begin it , the better . ’
#Text=‘ I only said “ if ” ! ’ poor Alice pleaded in a piteous tone .
#Text=The two Queens looked at each other , and the Red Queen remarked , with a little shudder , ‘ She SAYS she only said “ if” -- ’
#Text=‘ But she said a great deal more than that ! ’ the White Queen moaned , wringing her hands . ‘ Oh , ever so much more than that ! ’
#Text=‘ So you did , you know , ’ the Red Queen said to Alice . ‘ Always speak the truth -- think before you speak -- and write it down afterwards . ’
#Text=‘ I ’m sure I did n’t mean -- ’ Alice was beginning , but the Red Queen interrupted her impatiently .
#Text=‘ That ’s just what I complain of ! You SHOULD have meant !
#Text=What do you suppose is the use of child without any meaning ?
#Text=Even a joke should have some meaning -- and a child ’s more important than a joke , I hope .
#Text=You could n’t deny that , even if you tried with both hands . ’
#Text=‘ I do n’t deny things with my HANDS , ’ Alice objected .
#Text=‘ Nobody said you did , ’ said the Red Queen . ‘ I said you could n’t if you tried . ’
#Text=‘ She ’s in that state of mind , ’ said the White Queen , ‘ that she wants to deny SOMETHING -- only she does n’t know what to deny ! ’
#Text=‘ A nasty , vicious temper , ’ the Red Queen remarked ; and then there was an uncomfortable silence for a minute or two .
#Text=The Red Queen broke the silence by saying to the White Queen , ‘ I invite you to Alice ’s dinner-party this afternoon . ’
#Text=The White Queen smiled feebly , and said ‘ And I invite YOU . ’
#Text=‘ I did n’t know I was to have a party at all , ’ said Alice ; ‘ but if there is to be one , I think I ought to invite the guests . ’
#Text=‘ We gave you the opportunity of doing it , ’ the Red Queen remarked : ‘ but I daresay you ’ve not had many lessons in manners yet ? ’
#Text=‘ Manners are not taught in lessons , ’ said Alice . ‘ Lessons teach you to do sums , and things of that sort . ’
#Text=‘ And you do Addition ? ’ the White Queen asked .
#Text=‘ What ’s one and one and one and one and one and one and one and one and one and one ? ’
#Text=‘ I do n’t know , ’ said Alice . ‘ I lost count . ’
#Text=‘ She ca n’t do Addition , ’ the Red Queen interrupted .
#Text=‘ Can you do Subtraction ?
#Text=Take nine from eight . ’
#Text=‘ Nine from eight I ca n’t , you know , ’ Alice replied very readily : ‘ but -- ’
#Text=‘ She ca n’t do Subtraction , ’ said the White Queen . ‘ Can you do Division ?
#Text=Divide a loaf by a knife -- what ’s the answer to that ? ’
#Text=‘ I suppose -- ’ Alice was beginning , but the Red Queen answered for her . ‘ Bread-and-butter , of course .
#Text=Try another Subtraction sum .
#Text=Take a bone from a dog : what remains ? ’
#Text=Alice considered . ‘ The bone would n’t remain , of course , if I took it -- and the dog would n’t remain ; it would come to bite me -- and I ’m sure I should n’t remain ! ’
#Text=‘ Then you think nothing would remain ? ’ said the Red Queen .
#Text=‘ I think that ’s the answer . ’
#Text=‘ Wrong , as usual , ’ said the Red Queen : ‘ the dog ’s temper would remain . ’
#Text=‘ But I do n’t see how -- ’
#Text=‘ Why , look here ! ’ the Red Queen cried . ‘ The dog would lose its temper , would n’t it ? ’
#Text=‘ Perhaps it would , ’ Alice replied cautiously .
#Text=‘ Then if the dog went away , its temper would remain ! ’ the Queen exclaimed triumphantly .
#Text=Alice said , as gravely as she could , ‘ They might go different ways . ’ But she could n’t help thinking to herself , ‘ What dreadful nonsense we ARE talking ! ’
#Text=‘ She ca n’t do sums a BIT ! ’ the Queens said together , with great emphasis .
#Text=‘ Can YOU do sums ? ’ Alice said , turning suddenly on the White Queen , for she did n’t like being found fault with so much .
